    Several studies have shown that the information conveyed by bell-shaped
  tuning curves increases as their width decreases, leading to the notion that
  sharpening of tuning curves improves population codes. This notion, however,
  is based on assumptions that the noise distribution is independent among
  neurons and independent of the tuning curve width. Here we reexamine these
